CCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gekido1>gekido1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/25/03 7:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=12792.topic&index=81>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re:</span><hr size=1> You should be less worried about what your country does, or what you do for your country, and more worried about what you do in life.  It is better to be a great person than to live in a great country. <p>See you, Space Cowboy...</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=alucard1515>alucard1515</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator <img src=http://contest.polykarbon.com/badge1.gif></span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/25/03 8:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=12792.topic&index=82>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.undeadart.com/forum/alucard.gif width=100 height=94></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re:</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Customs, language, social affity with others that share your nationality, knowledge (knowledge regarding the atributes of your own nationality), religion isn't necsarily something that defines a nation but the Hebrew nation of ancient times can be a very good example of a nation without a land (they were nomads for a long time before ever finding Canaan again).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I think you're confusing nationality with ethnicity. That has more to do with culture and also ties into racial background. Nationalism is a fairly recent phenomenon, it certainly came long after the Biblical Hebrews.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The only drop of dominicanism he has is from his father's side, yet like I said nationalism isn't determined by race. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I think you misinterpretted my meaning a bit. I didn't mean that being born of someone from a particular nation makes you a part of of that nation and it's culture, just that it's more likely that you may identify with it, even if in part. Not to mention the obvious fact that if you're born a particular race in a particular nation, you're more likely to identify with it since that's all you've known.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Nationality isn't bonded to a citizenship, nationality is much more than a social security number and a passport.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Absolutely. You provided the example yourself of Latin Americans acclimating themselves to the culture they've become a part of. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> If I die will I stop being Dominican? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Yes. You will stop BEING Dominican, but you once were. And again, that's not nationalism. Nationalism, as you said yourself, isn't merely being a citizen of a nation. So, what if you weren't always Dominican? Did a Dominican person suddenly do all those things in life before becomming a citizen of that country? No, because you are not defined by what you are at the moment of death.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Better yet....are dead men nationless?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Well, I'm not really sure how to answer that. I think it's more complicated than you're putting it. Like I said, you might not have always been a citizen of that particular nation, so would you define someone as American if they only lived a small portion of their life there? Now it's a little easier to define if someone has lived all, or most, of their life in one place, but still, is a dead man anything other than dead? When a German guy dies, I guess he's a German corpse, but I wouldn't want to go much further than that.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And I don't mean a corpse, I mean the man/woman as in the personality (you would agree that we are much more than stardust).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I'm not sure what you're saying exactly. Their personality? You mean the idea of them after their dead? I don't think they've suddenly become something else now that they've died (other than dead), but they are not ACTIVELY anything anymore.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>My nationality isn't necesarily more important over all else. But it is one of the essencial components of what I am. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I think I worded that poorly. I meant &quot;your&quot; in a general sense, but I may have also been misinterpretting what you meant. I still think that you're placing more importance on it than you should. Don't get me wrong, there's absolutely nothing wrong with being proud of your nation and your cultural background. Everyone is in part, an important part, defined by where they come from. Even if you completely reject the culture you come from, that is still based on the ideals of that culture (in terms of its opposite). We're all shaped by our experiences, and the experience from one country to another is not going to be the same. The problem isn't in accepting that your culture is unique and different from others, it's getting caught up in those differences and championing them above the similarities you share with everyone, even those OUTSIDE of your culture/nation/whatever. If one is caught up so much in what is important to ME and MY culture alone, then you're bound to ignore the others' side. I'm not saying your, or hikagun, is doing this, but I still think you're too invested in defining yourself as part of that group.<br>
<br>
<br>
As a little note (and I'm not doing this to be obnoxious), I thought I'd include the dictionary definitions I looked up for nationalism and ethnicity. I don't want to end up disagreeing when we actually agree just because we're understanding the meaning of the same words we use differently. If you think the definitions are incomplete or wrong, fine. Just know that when I use the words, these definitions are what I'm going by. I realize that words take on a life of their own and sometimes have different conotations for different people, but I try (keyword, try) to use them consistenly to reduce confusion.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>eth·nic·i·ty    P   Pronunciation Key  (th-ns-t)<br>
n.<br>
<br>
Ethnic character, background, or affiliation.<br>
An ethnic group.<br>
an ethnic quality or affiliation resulting from racial or cultural ties; &quot;ethnicity has a strong influence on community status relations&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>na·tion·al·ism    P   Pronunciation Key  (nsh-n-lzm, nshn-)<br>
n.<br>
<br>
Devotion to the interests or culture of one's nation.<br>
The belief that nations will benefit from acting independently rather than collectively, emphasizing national rather than international goals.<br>
Aspirations for national independence in a country under foreign domination.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <p><html>
