Just replace nation with world. Again, nothing wrong with pride in your nation or cultural background, but there's a larger picture. And even nationalistic people consider themselves a part of smaller communities, such as states, cities, or even smaller communities. I don't see why it would be any different if we shifted from nationalism. Ties to your country wouldn't disappear, but people wouldn have a better view of the large picture.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I agree with your &quot;worldview&quot; nationalism. I myself consider myself a cosmopolitan. But a cosmopolitan world must be organized and thus people must have a clear idea of their own particular nationality. I think we both have covered common ground and finally come to a point in which we would have to face the great question: How can a cosmopolitan world truely work? This takes time and patience. I think that no matter what this type of &quot;worldview&quot; nationalism will come to us one of these days. Its innevitable. Not just because of the goblalistic movements that we see today but because already people are making plans for it and are trying to imagine how it would all be. Haven't you noticed that almost all movies, novels, comics, etc. speak of a future world that is dominated by a pseudo-united nations? Sci-fi writers never speak of the future reffering themselves to specific nations but of a world with a comunity of nations and most of the time simply say &quot;human kind&quot;. It's never &quot;Martians agianst Americans&quot; or &quot;Robots against the French&quot;, its most of the time human kind as a whole facing an enemy or challenge. This may be a very vague example but I find it incredibly natural for Sci-fi writers to propose a cosmopolitan future. This may be sad but it could be that in the only situation that the world can truely come together would be in a situation of possible<br>
 massive extinction of the human race. I really wouldn't want to wait for that threat ever to arrive before the world comes together and unifies all nations. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=japanesenationalist>Japanese Nationalist</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/27/03 11:26 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=12792.topic&index=87>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.japanorama.com/images/flag_waving_ag.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Encarta article on nationalism</span><hr size=1> In the year 1999 a space fortress will crash into a small island in the south Pacific.  When we fight the interstellar aliens we will be united as &quot;Human-kind&quot;.<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>I have found that common sense is rather uncommon.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=durakken>Durakken</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/27/03 11:58 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=12792.topic&index=88>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Encarta article on nationalism</span><hr size=1> it's much less the threat but the realization that there are beings out there more powerful than us and we don't want that...now do we? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=to